"tee" command is used store and view at the same time. 
the command is named after theT-splitter used in plumbing. it can be both displayed and saved at same time.

  calvin@localhost:~$ echo "hello there" 
this will only display the text

  calvin@localhost:~$ echo "hello there" > mytext.txt
this will write to mytext.txt file not displayin anything on the screen

  calvin@localhost:~$ echo "hello there" | tee mytext.txt
this will both dispay and write inside mytext.txt
Note: after i try to write something again and use the exact command it will remove the old text and write the new one

so, to prevent that we can use this;
  calvin@localhost:~$ echo "hello there" | tee -a mytext.txt


to see how many character we have in mytext.txt we can run;
  calvin@localhost:~$ wc -c mytext.txt


Not: with tee command we can create a file and write inside and display.
calvin@localhost:~$ echo "hello there" | tee mytext.txt text.txt filetext.txt
